defaultThe concept of shared fields of practice, of which home dialysis is one 
defaultexample, requires collaboration and equity among health care professionals to ensure that the impact of change is for the benefit of the patient. 
defaultAutomated Peritoneal Dialysis (APD) is a home-based therapy usually carried out by patients themselves.
default 
defaultTraining takes place in a renal unit or specialist training centre in all aspects of care.
default 
defaultThe parent unit regularly follows up patients either in clinic or in the community.
default 
defaultHowever, many patients with end-stage renal disease are unable to undertake peritoneal dialysis (PD) on their own, yet would prefer treatment in their own homes.
default 
defaultIn particular, the majority of elderly patients are on the hospital based treatment, haemodialysis (HD) despite the problems and costs of transport, achieving vascular access and, often, poor tolerance of the HD process. 
defaultTo address this problem, assisted PD using community 
defaultHealthcare Assistants h
defaultas been developed.
default 
defaultHealthcare assistants visit the patient’s home once a day to check the previous day’s treatment, check the patient’s wellbeing and set up the dialysis for the next treatment.
default 
defaultThe healthcare assistant is trained to observe for a range of sign and symptoms and to call the patient’s parent renal unit should they have concerns.
defaultThis system has been operating in the UK for almost six years and seen great success.
default 
defaultOver 250 patients are currently using the service which represents almost 10% of the PD population, all of whom would not be able to have a home based treatment if the service was not available.
default 
defaultThe system required collaboration and team work between the NHS renal unit, the home care provider and the nursing support organisation to enable seamless high quality care.
defaultThe implications of an ageing population for the prevalence and type of long term conditions, together with evidence about the extent to which existing services will have the capacity to meet future demanddefaultThe implications of an ever increasing elderly population will inevitably impact on the prevalence and type of long term conditions experienced.
default 
defaultIn many long term disease areas, as treatments improve, patients live for longer and thus are susceptible to a greater number of co-morbidities.
default 
defaultFor example people with the bleeding di
defaultsorder haemophilia, would
default have an average survival of
default 15 years if born in 1960, whereas today they have a normal life expectancy as techniques such as prophylaxis are now used to better manage their condition.
default 
defaultIn addition, treatments for long term diseases are now offered to older patients than previously.
default 
defaultThus, more patients are being treated for more diseases with more treatments than before.
defaultCapacity planning
default therefore
default needs to be much more holistic
default than in the past
default, and 
defaultconsider all available locations for care.
default 
defaultI
defaultntegrat
defaultion between primary, secondary, community and social care needs to be factored into capacity planning and the use of ho
defaultme care
default considered for a greater proportion of patients
default.
default 
defaultRemote
default monitoring systems 
defaultand electronic health records should be
default considered as 
defaultintegral to the support of patients and these must be accessible to patients as well as clinicians in both primary and secondary care
default.
